<Layout title="Yacht Broker Mortgage · Schedule C 1099 Commission, Co-Broker Splits, MarineMax W-2 Hybrid, Charter Management Fees &amp; Superyacht Brokerage Specialist - Fort Lauderdale" description="Yacht broker mortgage from a local Fort Lauderdale lender for new yacht brokers in years 1-3 building dock relationships and listing inventory, established brokerage-tier brokers at Denison Yachting, HMY Yacht Sales, United Yacht Sales, Galati Yacht Sales, Atlantic Yacht & Ship, Allied Marine, and Worth Avenue Yachts handling brokerage-tier vessels $200K-$3M, new yacht dealer sales reps at MarineMax (NYSE: HZO) selling Sea Ray, Boston Whaler, Azimut, Galeon, and Aviara models with W-2 hybrid base + variable + manufacturer override structure, senior top-producing brokers at $500K+ annual commission, superyacht brokers at international firms including Northrop & Johnson, Burgess Yachts, Edmiston, Fraser Yachts, IYC (International Yacht Company), and Worth Avenue Yachts handling $10M-$100M+ vessels with substantial commission income, brokerage owners and managing partners combining personal production with practice equity, and brokers with adjacent yacht charter management businesses earning central agent fees on client vessel charter revenue. Schedule C 1099-NEC commission income under Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02 with 24-month averaging plus rigorous Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for Schedule C deductions covering FLIBS (Fort Lauderdale International Boat Show) and other major boat show participation including Palm Beach International Boat Show, Miami International Boat Show, Cannes Yachting Festival, and Monaco Yacht Show, marketing and yacht listing platform fees at Yatco, YachtWorld, and BoatHistoryReport, E&O errors and omissions insurance, IYBA (International Yacht Brokers Association) membership dues and CPYB (Certified Professional Yacht Broker) credentialing fees, Florida Yacht and Ship Broker license through FLHSMV and bond requirements, captain expenses for sea trials, fuel and dock fees for vessel inspections, and international travel expenses. New yacht dealer W-2 income under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average for MarineMax and other dealer reps with base + variable commission + manufacturer override bonuses for hitting volume thresholds + quarterly/annual sales contest bonuses + RSU vesting from LTIP. S-corp election treatment under Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02 for top producers at $400K+ entity income combining W-2 reasonable compensation with K-1 distributions from remaining net commission income. Conventional Conforming, Conventional Jumbo, S-corp Self-Employed, Bank Statement Non-QM, and Asset-Depletion Non-QM loan program options. Fort Lauderdale yachting capital concentration context, FLIBS as primary annual industry event, MarineMax consolidation of new yacht retail, 2020-2022 yacht boom and 2023-2024 normalization, superyacht market growth at top tier, and yacht charter business adjacency.">
